english:
  title: A Letter Commending Tal-ga
  author: Jung Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Day by day heterodoxy flourishes while our Way declines, driving the people into the realm of beasts and plunging them into depths of suffering. The hearts of all under heaven flow unrestrained into chaos, with no proper order to anchor them. Alas, what anguish this brings! Who then shall set things right? Only through learning that is grounded in truth and virtue that reaches deeply into our Way—only when such people command the trust and obedience of the masses—can order be restored.

    Yet the common people are ignorant and foolish, knowing neither what to embrace nor what to reject. Should one in position of influence arise and refute heterodoxy, the people abandon it; should he promote it, the people echo his words. This is because the people know only that they must trust and obey the accomplished, while remaining ignorant that the Way itself contains both error and truth.

    In ancient times, Mencius, though poor and dwelling among commoners, ultimately refuted Yang Zhu and Mo Di, elevated Confucius, and all under heaven followed him—because his virtue had reached deep understanding and possessed the power to command the trust of the realm. Xiao Yan, though ignorant and benighted, succeeded in promoting Buddhism and had all under heaven follow him—because his high position possessed such power to command obedience. Thus Confucius spoke of it: "The virtue of the gentleman is wind; the virtue of the common people is grass. When wind blows over grass, it must bend." This is what he meant.

    From that time onward, with no wise rulers above and no true scholars below, teaching declined in the world while heterodox doctrines spread unchecked. Those in positions of influence joined in promoting them. Alas, the harms that have resulted defy enumeration!

    When the Song dynasty flourished, true scholars appeared in succession, grasping the abandoned classics to restore the broken transmission of the Way, holding fast to our doctrine while refuting heterodoxy—and scholars followed like wind-blown grass. This too came about because they witnessed virtue reaching deep understanding and trusted accordingly. Yet what a tragedy that virtue existed without position, unable to propagate the Way broadly or uproot the poisonous words of heterodoxy entirely.

    Still, the scholars of the Central Kingdom, relying on their teachings, made it their responsibility to hold fast to our Way and refute heterodoxy. Though the corruption runs deep and cannot be swiftly eradicated, one may yet hope for the restoration of our Way.

    But in the East, the corruption runs far deeper. The people devoutly believe and reverently embrace heterodoxy, while those called great scholars themselves compose songs of praise, amplifying its influence with such fanfare. The benighted masses simply follow what the accomplished above them favor. Thus the teaching of the ancient kings falls into silence—all that enters eye and ear is heterodoxy alone.

    Infants in their swaddling clothes learn its words as they begin to speak; in play they mimic its gestures. Habit becomes nature; they grow comfortable in error, unaware it is wrong. Corruption takes root in the heart, hardened beyond remedy. Even the brilliant are dazzled by its empty profundities; even the savage are moved by its promises of blessing and curse. All revere and embrace it, abandoning ethics and destroying humanity. Customs decay into chaos; families impoverish themselves and scatter—the descent into bestiality and suffering seems endless.

    Yet by Heaven's fortune, the inborn nature cannot be entirely severed. Even amid the turbulent currents, one or two luminous scholars emerge, recognizing heterodoxy's harm. They debate privately, sometimes offering arguments to the world that move some to awakening—proof that the heart of righteousness dwells in all. Yet lacking position, the people remain unconverted.

    When one debates with the heterodox themselves, they possess this heart too, know their error, and often find their words exhausted. Yet shamed to yield, they grasp for victory alone, wielding the authority of lords and ministers who revere the Buddha, the praise of great scholars—and thus they counter the debater: "If this were unrighteous, would Minister So trust it? With his position and virtue behind such devotion, do you presume yourself his superior?"

    Should the debater respond: "Though exalted to minister, he has not studied the Way; though called great scholar, his learning lacks truth. One must consult one's own heart and discern right from wrong—why accept his words simply because he utters them?"—such speech brings only the charge of subordinate presuming to judge the superior, and the people turn away, calling him mad. Thus the debater falls silent, while the heterodox puff with triumph, believing their argument has prevailed.

    So we see that heterodoxy's poison cannot be overcome by tongue alone, nor the confusion of the masses by reason alone. Only through learning grounded in truth and virtue reaching deep understanding—only through one whom the people can trust and follow—can order be restored.

    My friend Tal-ga is such a man. Though Tal-ga lacks position, his learning has long commanded the trust of scholars for its correctness, and his virtue has long earned their respect for its authentic reach. Even one as dull and unworthy as myself, dismissing the world's ridicule, took up the task of refuting heterodoxy by relying upon Tal-ga as my anchor. Surely Heaven sent Tal-ga as a blessing to our Way.

    Yet recently I hear whispers that Tal-ga studies the Lankavatara Sutra and seems bewitched by Buddhism like others. I replied: "If Tal-ga does not study it, how will he recognize its poison? His study aims to find its sickness and cure it—not to perfect its doctrine!" And I have said privately: "I pledge that Tal-ga will not be seduced."

    But I recall how Han Yu spoke once with a Buddhist master, and later ages seized upon this as proof—opening the gates to endless rumor. Tal-ga has become one whom others trust and follow. His actions now bear upon whether our Way will flourish or fade—he cannot but guard himself carefully. Moreover, our people's hearts grow ever more darkened, their confusion easier to deepen, their awakening harder to achieve. I earnestly entreat Tal-ga to reflect upon this.
  footnotes:
    - 'Lankavatara Sutra (Lengjia jing/능엄경): Jung Do-jeon uses Tal-ga''s study of this Buddhist text as a concrete example of how even virtuous scholars studying heterodox texts to understand and refute them may face suspicion from the masses.'
    - 'Han Yu (韓昌黎): Tang dynasty Confucian scholar famous for his anti-Buddhist stance, yet who once held philosophical discourse with a Buddhist monk, which later generations used as evidence against him—Jung Do-jeon''s cautionary example for Tal-ga.'
    - 'The Way (道): In Neo-Confucian context, refers to the orthodox teachings of Confucianism and the moral-philosophical system derived from Confucian and Mencian thought, as opposed to Buddhist and Daoist ''heterodoxy.'''
